Exercise 4

There are 3 conditions for interference: Random, Normal, Independence \ The sample is random
The sample skew is normal ?
-> If the skew is not normal (right skew) or it has an unknown parent population, the sample size must be large (n 30)
The sample is independent (n 10% of population 13583 / 4.9 million high school students from 1991-2019) 

yrbss %>%
  group_by(physical_3plus) %>%
  filter(!is.na(weight)) %>%
  dplyr::count(physical_3plus)

Exercise 6

No values are greater than obs_stat
Since the p-value is less than 0.05, we can reject the null hypothesis

obs_diff <- yrbss %>%
  specify(weight ~ physical_3plus) %>%
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("yes", "no"))
## Warning: Removed 1219 rows containing missing values.
obs_diff
## Response: weight (numeric)
## Explanatory: physical_3plus (factor)
## # A tibble: 1  1
##    stat
##   <dbl>
## 1  1.77
null_dist <- yrbss %>%
  specify(weight ~ physical_3plus) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>%
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("yes", "no"))
## Warning: Removed 1219 rows containing missing values.
null_dist
## Response: weight (numeric)
## Explanatory: physical_3plus (factor)
## Null Hypothesis: independence
## # A tibble: 1,000  2
##    replicate    stat
##        <int>   <dbl>
##  1         1  0.420 
##  2         2 -0.0761
##  3         3 -0.240 
##  4         4  0.535 
##  5         5  0.190 
##  6         6 -0.287 
##  7         7  0.349 
##  8         8 -0.146 
##  9         9 -0.475 
## 10        10  0.762 
## #  with 990 more rows
ggplot(data = null_dist, aes(x = stat)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

null_dist %>%

Exercise 7

Were 95% sure the difference of averages of all weights of those who dont work 3 days and greater and those that do falls somewhere between -2.424441 and -1.124728

DATA606::inference(y = yrbss$weight, 
                   x = yrbss$physical_3plus, 
                   null = 0,
                   est = "mean",
                   type = "ht",
                   alternative = "twosided", 
                   method = "theoretical")

z = 1.96


upperCI <- yrbss_mean + z * (yrbss_sd / sqrt(yrbss_count))

upperCI
## [1] 1.693071
lowerCI <- yrbss_mean - z * (yrbss_sd / sqrt(yrbss_count))

lowerCI
## [1] 1.689411

  summary
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   1.270   1.600   1.680   1.691   1.780   2.110
yrbss_heights$height %>%
  t.test
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  .
## t = 1811.7, df = 12578, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.689411 1.693071
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  1.691241
ciBounds <- yrbss_heights$height %>%
  CI

ciBounds
##    upper     mean    lower 
## 1.693071 1.691241 1.689411
meanCIBounds <- yrbss_heights$height %>%
  MeanCI

meanCIBounds
##     mean   lwr.ci   upr.ci 
## 1.691241 1.689411 1.693071
c(upperCI, ciBounds[[1]], meanCIBounds[[3]])
## [1] 1.693071 1.693071 1.693071
c(lowerCI, ciBounds[[3]], meanCIBounds[[2]])
## [1] 1.689411 1.689411 1.689411
paste("Interval:", ciBounds[[1]] - ciBounds[[3]])
## [1] "Interval: 0.00365958721649173"
DATA606::inference(y = yrbss_heights$height, 
                   type = "ci", 
                   est = "mean",
                   alternative = "twosided", 
                   method = "theoretical")

Exercise 9

The range is smaller at 90% confidence because were less confident, which means by reducing the range, the true average is less likely to fall within it

z <- 1.645



yrbss_heights$height %>%
  t.test(conf.level = 0.90)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  .
## t = 1811.7, df = 12578, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 90 percent confidence interval:
##  1.689705 1.692777
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  1.691241
ciBounds <- yrbss_heights$height %>%
  CI(ci = 0.90)

ciBounds
##    upper     mean    lower 
## 1.692777 1.691241 1.689705
meanCIBounds <- yrbss_heights$height %>%
  MeanCI(conf.level = 0.90)

meanCIBounds
##     mean   lwr.ci   upr.ci 
## 1.691241 1.689705 1.692777
paste("Upper bound:", ciBounds[[1]])
## [1] "Upper bound: 1.69277653368189"
paste("Lower bound:", ciBounds[[3]])
## [1] "Lower bound: 1.68970538061972"
paste("Interval:", ciBounds[[1]] - ciBounds[[3]])
## [1] "Interval: 0.00307115306216632"
DATA606::inference(y = yrbss_heights$height, 
                   type = "ci", 
                   est = "mean", 
                   alternative = "twosided",

                   conflevel = 0.90)

Exercise 12

H0: There is no correlation between weight and hours of sleep on a school night
HA: There is a correlation between weight and hours of sleep on a school night
Since the p-value is less than 0.05, we can reject the null hypothesis

yrbss_weight_school_night_hours_sleep <- yrbss %>%
  filter(!is.na(weight)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(school_night_hours_sleep))



oilabs::inference(y = weight, 
                  x = school_night_hours_sleep, 
                  data = yrbss_weight_school_night_hours_sleep,
                  null = 0,
                  statistic = "mean",
                  order = c(yesLabel, noLabel),
                  type = "ht",
                  alternative = "greater", 
                  method = "theoretical")
